$* TO DISCOVER ALIVE HOST/S IN A NETWORK:-

         # nmap -sn <IP>  OR  nmap -sP <IP> 
                  -> Here, -sP ping scan (old option to check if host is up no port scan)
                           -sn no port scan ( modern option skip port scan , just do host discovery)
         # nmap -R -sn <IP> 
                  -> with -R nmap tries to check host name (reverse DNS) even if host is dead.

$* effecient way to use:-

         # nmap -sn <IP subnet> -oG hosts.txt
                  -> To store the result in a file.
                  here, -oG is for greppable output
                         hosts.txt is file name containing the result of -sn command ie ip , status and hostname (if resolved).
         # grep Up hosts.txt | awk '{print $2}' > live_hosts.txt
                  -> To store the alive IPs into a file.
                  here, with grep takes the line which has status "Up".
                        then print second field ie IPs in the live_hosts.txt file
                            ( Host: 192.168.1.5 (printer.local)   Status: Up) $2 is IP
         # nmap -sV -iL live_hosts.txt
                  -> run a full port scan only on those live hosts. (*Focus resources where it matters)
                  here, -iL input from list file
                        -sV service/version detection

$* PORT SCANNING:-

         {TCP}
         # nmap -sT <IP>
                  -> TCP connect scan. TCP three way handshake( SYN[S , SYN-ACK, ACK)
                  -> No root privileges. It is "loud" as full connection is established.
         # sudo nmap -sS <IP>
                  -> SYN stealth scan. Half open handshake (SYN, SYN-ACK, RST[reset])
                  -> More stealthier(connection is never fully established) and faster but need root privileges.
      
         {UDP}
         # sudo nmap -sU <IP>
                  -> Scan for most common 1000 UDP ports
         # sudo nmap -sU -F <IP>
                  -> Scan for most common 100 UDP ports
         # sudo nmap -sU -p <PORT> <IP>
                  -> For specific ports
         # sudo nmap -sU -sV <IP>
                  -> To force nmap to find out if port is actually open 
      * # sudo nmap -sS -sU <IP>
                  -> Scanning TCP and UDP Together.

         {ACK scan}
         # nmap -sA <IP>
                  -> Used for firewall mapping. Doesn't tell if port is open, only whether it's filtered/unfiltered.

         {Stealth scan}
         # nmap -sN <IP>
                  -> Null Scan. Closed port responds with (RST) and Open port no response (open|filtered)
                  -> no flags, empty TCP packet
         # nmap -sF <IP>
                  -> FIN Scan. Same as Null scan.
                  -> TCP packet with only FIN flag
         # nmap -sX <IP>
                  -> Xmas Scan. Same as Null scan.
                  -> TCP packet with FIN + PSH + URG flags.

$* SERVICE AND VERSION DETECTION:-

         # sudo nmap -sV <IP>
                  -> The core version scan flag. Tells Nmap to stop guessing and to actively  probe the service to find its exact name and version.
         # sudo nmap -sV --version-intensity <0-10> <IP>
                  -> Controlling Scan precision, 0 for light scan and 9 for max intensity scan
         # sudo nmap -sV --packet-trace <IP>
                  -> Show the actual raw data Nmap is exchanging with target server
         # sudo nmap -sS -sV <IP> or sudo nmap -sU -sV <IP>
                  -> Combining protocols with version detection.

$* OS DETECTION:-

         # sudo nmap -O <IP>
                  -> Standard OS fingerprinting. Requires 1 open and 1 closed port.
         # sudo nmap -O --osscan-guess <IP> (OR) sudo nmap -O --fuzzy <IP>
                  -> Forces Nmap to provide percentage based guesses if no perfect match exists.
         # sudo nmap -O --osscan-limit <IP>
                  -> Skip the target which lack the required open/closed ports condition.
         # sudo nmap -O --max-os-tries <number> <IP>
                  -> Limits the no of times Nmap will cycle its probes on a glitchy target.
     

         

         
